==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Arabic
<hw>Ar"a*bic</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Arabicus</ets>, fr. <ets>Arabia</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining
to Arabia or the Arabians.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Arabic numerals</b></col> or
<col><b>figures</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the nine digits, 1, 2, 3, etc.,
and the cipher 0.</cd> -- <col><b>Gum arabic</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Gum</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Arabic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Arabic
<hw>Ar"a*bic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The language of the
Arabians.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>Arabic</xex> is a Semitic language, allied to
the Hebrew. It is very widely diffused, being the language in which all
Moslems must read the Koran, and is spoken as a vernacular tongue in
Arabia, Syria, and Northern Africa.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Arabical</ent>⟦br⟧
